  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements aimed at preventing money laundering:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Global standard-setting body for anti-money laundering efforts\n- Develops policies to combat financial crimes\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention Against Corruption\n\n3. Basel Committee Guidelines\n- International banking standards for detecting and preventing money laundering\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Standards\n- Provides guidelines for member countries to combat financial crimes\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Comprehensive regulations for EU member states\n\n6. Egmont Group\n- International network of financial intelligence units\n- Facilitates information sharing between countries\n\nMost countries have national laws implementing these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include significant fines and criminal prosecution.\n\nThese frameworks help prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
